  "articleSummary": "The article argues that well-designed multiple-choice questions (MCQs) are powerful pedagogical tools, particularly in technical fields like programming, because they reveal learners’ misconceptions through thoughtfully crafted distractors. The core thesis is that effective MCQs teach not just by identifying correct answers but by modeling common errors—such as syntax from other languages, outdated practices, or near-correct patterns—that reflect real-world misunderstandings. Using a PostgreSQL quiz example, the author demonstrates how a single question can serve multiple learning levels (beginner to advanced) by exposing learners’ mental models. The tone is analytical and reflective, blending personal experience with instructional theory, and emphasizes that MCQ creation demands \"instructional honesty\" by forcing authors to confront gaps in their own explanations. The intended audience includes educators and technical writers seeking to improve their teaching tools through structured feedback loops and precise conceptual framing.",
